### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

router

### Is this a regression?

Yes

### Description

The project is not new but we keep it up-to-date version-wise. That being said, we haven't switched to standalone components fully and only use them for shared components with one exception that I'll cover next.

The app is initialized via
```
platformBrowserDynamic()
  .bootstrapModule(AppModule)
  .catch((error: Error) => console.error(error))
```

Our routing looks like this:
```
export const ROUTES: Routes = [
  { path: '', redirectTo: 'login', pathMatch: 'full' },
  { path: 'activate/:token', component: Dummy, canActivate: [ActivateRedirectGuard] },
  {
    matcher: groupOnboardingPageMatch,
    component: Dummy,
    canActivate: [GroupRegistrationRedirectGuard]
  },
  {
    path: 'manage-membership/:groupId',
    canActivate: [BrowserGuard, ManageMembershipRedirectGuard],
    component: Dummy
  },
  { path: 'login', component: LoginComponent, canActivate: [BrowserGuard, LoginGuard] },
  {
    path: 'reset-password/:token',
    loadChildren: () => import('./module/reset-password/reset-password.module').then((m) => m.ResetPasswordModule)
  },
  {
    path: 'invited-organization/:registration_code',
    loadChildren: () =>
      import('./module/register-invited-organization/register-invited-organization.module').then(
        (m) => m.RegisterInvitedOrganizationModule
      )
  },
  {
    path: 'dashboard',
    component: DashboardComponent,
    canActivate: [BrowserGuard, DashboardAuthGuard],
    canActivateChild: [BrowserGuard, DashboardAuthGuard],
    children: [
      { path: '', redirectTo: 'membership', pathMatch: 'full' },
      ...
      {
        path: 'economy',
        loadChildren: () =>
          import('./module/dashboard/tabs/economy-tab/economy-tab.module').then((m) => m.EconomyTabModule)
      },
      // {
      //   path: 'accounting',
      //   loadComponent: () =>
      //     import('./module/dashboard/tabs/accounting-tab/accounting-dashboard/accounting-dashboard.component').then(
      //       (m) => m.AccountingDashboardComponent
      //     )
      // },
      {
        path: 'locations',
        loadChildren: () =>
          import('./module/dashboard/tabs/locations-tab/locations-tab.module').then((m) => m.LocationsTabModule)
      }
      ...
    ]
  },
  { path: '404', component: NothingFoundComponent },
  { path: 'not-supported-browser', component: NotSupportedBrowserComponent },
  { path: '**', component: NothingFoundComponent }
]
```

It's imported into `app.module.ts` via `RouterModule.forRoot(ROUTES)`.

As you can see, under the "dashboard" route we're using modules to combine multiple components together and lazy-load those child components all at once. So each of those modules (like economy, locations and many more that I've omitted) have `RouterModule.forChild()` with the inner routes for every child component.

Notice the commented out "accounting" route. It's the only route that directly lazy-loads a standalone component. It's done this way because the library it uses now requires it to be standalone.

Here's the issue though. While trying to expand the "accounting" route to become a module like every other module (to have more routes inside) and simply import the AccountingDashboardComponent into that new module, I noticed that the runtime is broken with a random error `Error: Invalid provider for the NgModule 'NgxsRootModule' - only instances of Provider and Type are allowed, got: [..., ..., ?undefined?, ?undefined?, ?undefined?, ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ...]`.

In fact it doesn't even work if I **remove** the lazy-loading and directly state `component: AccountingDashboardComponent` for that route. In fact, and that's the weirdest part, it will fail even if I remove the "accounting" route completely...

Days of digging into this have lead me to conclusion that it has been broken in the version 18, because I can easily remove the route in my old branch that uses Angular 17 and everything's fine.

More specifically I found that in Angular 18 _I basically have to have at least one standalone component in my router in order for it to stop erroring_. I turned `ResetPasswordModule` (which only represents one component) into a standalone component and imported it directly into the router via `loadComponent` and that eliminated the error. Now I can update my old "accounting" route without any errors.

That is certainly not the resolution I want, something's not right, I want to understand it and fix it. I don't have to be forced to use standalone components this way.


### Please provide the exception or error you saw

```true
Error: Invalid provider for the NgModule 'NgxsRootModule' - only instances of Provider and Type are allowed, got: [..., ..., ?undefined?, ?undefined?, ?undefined?, ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ..., ...]
```


